{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/args-and-kwargs-d89bdf56d49b", "time": 1683018345.985131, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/args-and-kwargs-d89bdf56d49b/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "What are *Args and **Kwargs in Python? | by Toni Domenech Borrell | Towards Data Science", "h1": "What are *Args and **Kwargs in Python?", "description": "If you have been programming Python for a while now surely you\u2019ll have had a doubt in how to use a function properly. You went to the paper and have met with *args and **kwargs inside the parameter\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [], "all_paragraphs": ["If you have been programming Python for a while now surely you\u2019ll have had a doubt in how to use a function properly. You went to the paper and have met with *args and **kwargs inside the parameter of this function.", "In matplotlib or in seaborn (to name but a few) there are regularly these words in the attributes of a function. Let\u2019s take a look at a caption.", "When I started seeing these attributes my brain usually did like them didn\u2019t exist. Until I recalled the power of this attribute and the commodity they provide. Using them your functions can be a lot more versatile and scalable.", "Usually, the functions have some \u2018natural\u2019 attributes and each parameter are regularly predefined. For example, in the matplotlib function seen above, we have the \u201cData\u201d attribute where its value \u201c=None\u201d is predefined. This meaning that if you don\u2019t use a value in \u201cData\u201d the calling of the function will return an empty figure. A none by default.", "What happens with the *args and**kwargs seen above? The args here are usually used to introduce the data, x1, x2 whatsoever. And the kwargs are used for the tunning of your graph. The properties of each graph come determined with the kwargs you introduce. Linewidth, linestyle, or marker are just some of the keyworded attributes you could already be familiar with. So you have been already using this **kwargs-thing unconsciously.", "Let\u2019s dive deeper into this attributes:", "Sometimes we don\u2019t know how many values we will enter in a function. Here *args come to play.", "Imagine you want to do a function in order to add values. You don\u2019t know how many values you\u2019ll try to add. You can do a function for each number of terms. add_2_numbers, add_3_numbers, add_4_numbers and this can continue for a long time. However, you\u2019ll see this method is time-consuming and it\u2019s also very far from being an elegant one.", "You can simplify the problem seen above with a *args.", "This function will return you the sum of the args you want to give to it.", "Now imagine that you want to create a dictionary. This dictionary will be your personal agenda. You don\u2019t know a priori how much information you\u2019ll have of each person. So you need some malleability there.", "The name of **kwargs comes from keyworded arguments. So if you want your new introduced variables to have a given name (Firstname, age, Email\u2026) you can use all of them using kwargs.", "Disclaimer: Both *args and **kwargs are the prefered names by convention but what it really matters is the use of `*` and `**`. So if the last example seen you would like to put data instead of kwargs because it gives you more readability of the function you could do it without a problem if you conserve the \u2018**\u2019.", "I hope I have helped you with this Python Pill.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Theoretical Physicist. Data Scientist based on Barcelona. Working with AI. Ah, also a musician."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fd89bdf56d49b&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?opera